In article &lt;844@stride.Stride.COM&gt;, mitch@Stride.COM (Thomas Mitchell) writes:

I interpret the line below to mean I cannot quote the original article.
&gt; Copyright 1988 All Rights Reserved World Wide.  Pattent may be pending.

The original article proposed adding suffixes to the right hand side of 
real registered domain addresses.  The example of the proposed change was
that .stride.com become .stride.com.rno  (rno = airport code for Reno, NV
apparently).
  
  Most Internet sites pass mail directly via the Internet.
The problem the author sees is cross-country routing of mail on uucp.
The solution is a better mail transport mechanism not a change in an
already working domain-name system.  The creation of the .US domain to
handle small sites including the uucp sites should help with routing in
uucp and between Internet and non-Internet sites in any event.
I gather from the proposal that stride.com is not on the Internet directly.
I disagree with his idea as much as I disliked the BITNET proposal earlier.

